SOUR.ABBR: Acme Memories
SOUR.TITL: Acme Memories
SOUR.PUBL: Acme and District Historical Society - Acme, Alberta - 1979
SOUR.TEXT:
Page 468
Walter Whalley - by Mary Whalley
On May 19, 1904 the Cochrane family - consisting of our mot
her, Grace Cochrane, my brother Gordon, and myself, Mary, l
eft Ottawa, Ontario, tot take up homesteads on land ten o
r 12 miles west of what now is Acme. We were 20 miles eas
t of Crossfield whic was our nearest post office and town
. When we settled there, there were no roads, no fences, n
o settler's light, except for the three Davis bachelors far
ming on the fourth quarter of our section. Prior to our ar
rival my older brother, Douglas, had moved to a farm clos
e to Crossfield and we had come to join him.
In the year 1910 I married Walter Whalley, living on a home
stead close to Acme with his mother, Mrs. Margaret Whiddon
, and his sister, Nellie Whalley.
In the year 1911 or 1912 the Anglican Church, St. John th
e Divine, was built in Acme, all volunteer labour of the me
n. The women cooked and delivered a hot meal each day to t
he workers. Our first clergyman was the Rev. W. Attwood wh
o shingled the church roof unassisted. On completion of th
e building, Bishop Pinkham cam out and with Rev. Attwood as
sisting, our church was dedicated. Both clergymen stayed o
vernight with us in our home.
We farmed at Acme for two more years, then rented the far
m and moved to Calgary where our first two children, Ronni
e and Beth were born, Ronnie in 1915 and Beth in 1917. I
n 1922 we moved back to Acme where our third child, Margare
t, was born on the farm. The winters were very, very sever
e. When Margaret was born we had to put her in the warmin
g oven of our cookstove to keep her warm enough.

SOUR.ABBR: Obituary of Bern Breeden
SOUR.TITL: The Oregonian
SOUR.TEXT:
Page F10
A memorial service for Bern Breeden of Seaside will be a
t 2 p.m. Saturday in the Hughes Ransom Mortuary in Seaside.
Mr. Breeden died Monday in a Portland care center. He was 8
2.
He was born in Oklahoma in 1910, but moved to Portland a
s a child. He later worked as a construction supervisor fo
r Portland Road and Driveway Co. for more than 30 years.
He was a former member of the U.S. Coast Guard Auxiliary.
Survivors include a sister, Julianna Morrison of Portland
, and a brother, B.J. Curtner of Wilsonville.
Disposition was by cremation.
The family suggests that remembrances be contributions t
o a favorite charity.

SOUR.ABBR: Obituary of Evelyn Paula Breeden
SOUR.TITL: The Oregonian
SOUR.TEXT:
Page B8:
A memorial service for Evelyn Paula Breeden, a North Portla
nd resident, will be at 1 p.m. Wednesday in the chapel of R
ose City Cemetery and Funeral Home.
Mrs. Breeden died of lung cancer Sunday in a Portland car
e center. She was 82.
She was born March 19, 1910, in Edwall, Wash., and moved t
o Oregon with her family at the age of 6. Mrs. Breeden wa
s a homemaker. She had lived in North Portland for many yea
rs and briefly had done laboratory work for Good Samarita
n Hospital & Medical Center.
Mrs. Breeden is survived by her brother, Jack E. Morrison o
f Bend.
Disposition was by cremation.
The family suggests that remembrances be contributions t
o a favorite charity.

SOUR.ABBR: Obituary of Muriel Alice Nims
SOUR.TITL: The Oregonian
SOUR.TEXT:
Page C15:
A memorial service will be at 3 p.m. Tuesday, Nov. 19, 1996
, in Rose City Cemetery and Funeral Home for Muriel Alice N
ims, who died Nov. 14 of complications of Parkinson's disea
se at age 79.
Mrs. Nims was born Aug. 10, 1917, in Calgary, Alberta. In 1
946, she married C.H. Nims.
Surviving are her husband; daughter, Cheryl D. Rosen of Por
tland; sister, Estelle Lewin of Portland; one grandchild; a
nd two great-grandchildren.
Disposition will be by cremation. The family suggests remem
brances to Parkinson Center of Oregon in care of Oregon Hea
lth Sciences University Department of Neurology L-226.
